Energetics of Reproduction in Sternotherus odoratus

Lyranda Thiem

Introduction

The life history theory suggests a form of tradeoff in the allocation of energy into present and future offspring, which is determined by reproductive effort, mode of reproduction, and reproductive frequency(Shine 1980).Many reptiles lack parental care after oviposition. Turtles are of no exception; instead turtles invest all of their reproductive effort into their offspring prior to oviposition.Reproductive effort is directed towards mating, vitellogensis (producing a yolk sac), develeping the embryo, creating a shell layer, and retaining eggs within the oviduct until the environment is optimal for nesting.All known turtles today have the ability to retain eggs for an extended period of time.Some turtles such as the chicken turtle are capable of retaining eggs for half a year, while other turtles like snapping turtles are capable of retaining their eggs for two weeks once eggs have been fully shelled(Kuchling 1999). The primary goal of this study is to assess the energetic tradeoffs of egg retention as a form of parental care, and if so suggest how this would be a beneficial reproductive strategy if energy investments are low. To address this question we examined the metabolic rates of gravid females pre and post oviposition, males, and non-gravid metabolic rates using open and closed circuit respirometry

Hypothesis: Oviductal egg retention is a beneficial reproductive strategt because it permits flexibility in the timing of oviposition, but has minimal energetic costs.

Objective 1:Determine the energetic costs of retaining eggs for gravid females.For gravid females, retaining viable eggs (within the oviduct) is a beneficial strategy if the energetic cost is low. If this is true, we predict the duration of egg retention will be low compared to the energy investment for non-gravid females and males. Thereby egg retention should be a beneficial reproductive strategy

Objective 2: Determine the reproductive effort of gravid females throughout their oviductal egg retention period. We would predict that females will have increased metabolic rates early on in reproduction due to vitellogenesis (yolk sac formation). Their metabolic rates would then decreased as they approached oviposition.

Objective 3:Determine if metabolic rates differ between females gravid metabolic rates and their non-gravid metabolic rate.If the cost of retaining eggs in the oviduct is low then we would predict there would be no difference in gravid and non-gravid metabolic rates.d

Methods

-Turtles were collected using Jones Traps

-Turtles were marked, weighed, and length of carapace and plastron was measured

-Females were x-rayed to determine whether they were gravid

-Turtles housed for three days prior to sampling and allowed to become digestively post absorptive

-Open-circuit respirometry was used to measure CO2 production for 48 hrs.

-Closed-circuit respirometry was used to measures O2 consumption 24 hrs after oviposition

-Conversion factors were used to convert metabolic measurements to joules/hr

-Metabolic rates were adjusted for mass and an ANCOVA with a pairwise analysis was run

-A Mixed model was run to determine signficant effects on female metabolic rate

-Repeated measures ANOVA with a post hoc was run to determine if gravid metabolic rates over time were signficant

Site Description

Musk Turtles (Sternotherus odoratus) were captured from backwater sloughs along the Cumberland River, Cheatham County, Tennessee using Jones traps (Chandler et al.2017).Traps were baited with canned tuna or sardines and placed in water deep enough to be mostly submerged, which allowed them to be left overnight and be checked the following day. Traps were left in the same location for a week prior to being moved. Traps were placed in murky/muddy water with duckweed covering.Trapping was conducted during the reproductive season from mid-May to September (Mitchell 1985, Ernst 1986, Ford and Moll 2004).

Assuming "longitude" and "latitude" are longitude and latitude, respectively

Results

Adjusting for Egg Metabolism

Before we can run any tests we need to calculate energy produced during the respirometry run we need to convert our mL CO2/hr into joules/hr using conversion factors. The conversion factors were taken from Gessaman and Nagey 1988 and Reid et al 2009.

Egg energy expenditure: Conversion factor from Reid et al.2009 VO2 converstion factor= 20.1 J/ml O2

Turtle energy expenditure: Conversion factor from Gessaman and Nagy 1988 VCO2 converstion factor= 24.32 KJ/ml CO2

After converting metabolic rates from mLCO2/h to joules/h we need to them subtract the metabolic rates of the whole clutch from the respected gravid female because we only want to examine the gravid females metabolic rate.

Data Description

Below is a description of all the factor variables included within my data set.

Turtle_ID: 54 total individuals

Group: Gravid Females, Males, Non-Gravid Females

mlCO2/hr turtles: measured metabolic rates

Turtle_Mass: Individual turtle mass to the nearest gram

mlO2/min eggs: measured metabolic rates for whole clutch of eggs

Whole clutch mass: reported weigths(g) of the entire clutch for each gravid female

mlO2/hr eggs: measured metabolic rates for whole clutch of eggs

Joules/hr turtles: calculated joules per hour used my indivudal turtles using the conversion factor

Joules/hr whole clutch: calculated joules per hour used by the whole clutch from each gravid female

adj_energy_joules_turtles: subtracting the joules/hr for the clutch from each of the gravid females

All turtles have a positive correlation in metabolic rates (joules/hr) while accounting for the adjusted turtle mass (subtracting the gravid females clutch mass from her mass in order to get the actual mass of the female). From the graph it looks as though gravid females have a higher metabolic rate then do males and non-gravid females for the the reproductive season. We will run an ANCOVA with a pairwise test to determine if this is the case for these turtles.

Before running an ANCOVA and a pairwise test I ran the an autoplot to check for potential outliers. Here we see in the normal Q-Q plot that three values (16,15,36) could be potential outliers, however, they do not seem to deviate from the line too much so they may be okay.The first and third plot do not show any signficant pattern which is good.

Mixed Models

Discussion

The results of this study determined gravid females have a signficantly higher metabolic rate than males and non-gravid females due to retaining eggs for an extended period of time. The study also found gravid females have elevated metabolic rates from their non-gravid metabolic rates. Neither of these findinfs were that suprising since producing and maintianing an offspring has some costs associated with it. The costs of oviductal egg retention although elevated at the start of each trial was not signficantly different throughout gravidity.The next steps in this study it to search literature to calculate the energy investments into other stages of reproduction such as, vitellogensis.

Postponement in nesting is an advantageous strategy in reproductive success, primarily in allowing for flexibility in the timing of oviposition (Ewert 1991; Rafferty and Reina 2012). Extending egg retention can increase survivability of offspring because it allows for gravid females to wait until environmental conditions are optimal. Habitat conditions fluctuate resulting in females not finding sufficient nesting areas or sufficient water reserves in their body to activate oviposition (Bulhman 1995). Thus oviductal egg retention would be energetically beneficial to prematurely depositing eggs and if at all possible producing another clutch. Waiting to nest until after a rainfall would decrease the chances of predation on nest (Spencer et al.2001, Santos et al.2016). Predation rates are further decreased when egg retention is extended because synchronized hatching occurs within and among nests (Plotkin et al.1997). Extending egg retention ensures that eggs are all at the same stage of development (gastrula stage) before they are laid thus eggs or clutches hatch at the same time leading to increased survival rates among hatchlings due to predator dilution (Licht 1980, 1982; Licht et al.1982; Owens and Morris 1985). Synchronized hatching further increases survivability and increases reproductive fitness of adult females by decreasing the energetic cost of nest escape by offspring (Rusli et al.2016).
